Freedom to Make Life Choices Across Continents

Freedom to Make Life Choices Across Continents

Author

Abby Kotar, Lily Watson, Will Sorge

Published

December 6, 2023

Introduction

The World Happiness Report considers the âfreedom to make life choicesâ in its composite index of happiness. This subjective rating is measured by asking survey respondents to rate their perception of their freedom to make life choices on a numeric scale, the Cantril ladder, which is then factored into the index. The data was collected from 2008 to 2022. In this project, we focused on this aspect of the Happiness data set in order to evaluate how the freedom to make life choices in particular varies between different continents and regions, and how the perception of it might vary based on cultural factors. Additionally, we represented the data in three-year intervals going back to the early 2010âs, in order to observe how freedom has fluctuated over time in various countries. We expect that, while generally keeping pace with global events and various conditions of the respective time, people have a highly subjective view of their relative freedom level which can shift dramatically from year to year, not appearing to mirror any specific shift in the law or policy of their given country. We also expect the COVID-19 pandemic to accompany a noticeable drop in perceptions of freedom, as many governments were forced to balance individual liberty with public health imperatives.

In order to produce the various visualizations shown below, we added a package that attached country names to various continents and regions (since the Happiness data set does not do this already). We then filtered the data down to only the âfreedom to make life choicesâ column and used colnames to standardize naming, before plotting the data. The plots themselves required a fair amount of wrangling to aid present-ability and variety. We also observed a major confounder in the form of perceptions of corruption, manifesting both internally (based on survey responses) and externally (based on actual civic effects).

Results

First, we wanted to examine the proportions of high or low corruption, freedom and life ladder indexes by continent. Knowing each continent has a different number of countries within it, we wanted to look at proportions in order to get a better picture of the distribution of the data. We wanted to look at the relationships between levels of perceptions of corruption, freedom to make life choices, and life ladder. We thought that these might differ per continent based on different cultural values and ideas of what freedom means. When examining these proportions, we were looking for differences between continents to see if there a relationship between continents and different indexes. Based on these proportions, we would further examine the relationships between different continents that we think could explain some of these inequalities.

For perceptions of corruption and freedom to make life choices, we determined high would be above \(0.7\), medium would be above \(0.5\), and low would be below \(0.5\) based on the range of data seen in the graphs. Similarly, for life ladder index, above 7 is high, above 5 is middle, and below 5 is low.

In life ladder, Africa has 0% in the high life ladder section while Oceania has 0% in the low life ladder section. Africa has a majority in the low life ladder section, close to 83% while other Asia, Americas, and Europe have a majority in the middle.

For corruption, all continents except Oceania have a majority with a high corruption index. While Oceania has 0% in the high corruption, Europe has the second lowest at around 61%, and the second highest percentage in the low corruption section, 24%.

Hypothesis

Freedom to Make Life Choices in Europe vs Africa

In our initial analysis, we noticed a discrepancy between freedom to make life choices in Europe and Africa. Africa and Europe has similar minimums (the two lowest minimums) and similar maximums (Africa was 0.968 and Europe was 0.971) but the means were different (Africa was 0.692 and Europe was 0.765). We wanted to examine this difference in means further by using a hypothesis test to see if there was a relationship between continent and freedom to make life choices.

Null Hypothesis: There is no difference in freedom to make life choices by continent. \(H_0: F_E = F_A\) where \(F\) is freedom to make life choices

Alternative Hypothesis: There is a difference in freedom to make life choices between Europe and Africa. \(H_A: F_E \neq F_A\)

Based on our calculate p-value of 0, we can reject the null hypothesis. Adding more reps continues to keep the p value at 0. If our \(\alpha = 0.05\), \(\alpha <= p\) so we know we can reject the null hypothesis. Therefore, there seems to be a relationship between continent and the freedom to make life choices.

Perceptions of Corruption in Europe and Asia

One of our key questions was looking at how cultural differences manifest within the data. We believed that Europeans and Asians have different ways they perceive corruption within society due to different histories and cultural values. To examine this further, we created a hypothesis test to look at the differences in perception of corruption.

Null Hypothesis: There is no relationship between perceptions of corruption and continent.

\(H_0: C_E = C_A\) where \(C\) is perception of corruption.

Alternative Hypothesis: There is a relationship between perceptions of corruption and continent.

\(H_A: C_E \neq C_A\)

Based on the calculated p value of 0.0068, if our \(\alpha = 0.05\), \(\alpha >= p\) so we can reject the null hypothesis. Therefore, we can conclude that perceptions of corruption and continent are not independent for Europe and Asia.

Perceptions of Corruption by Region in the Americas

When separating the countries into continents, we noticed that North America and South America were grouped together. We wondered if this caused any discrepancy within the results of perceptions of corruption calculated for the Americas. Since the United States and Canada have not been on the receiving end of colonization or coup dâetats recently, we wondered if the mean perceptions of corruption in the Americas did not accurately represent the countries within in. Therefore, we did a hypothesis test to if there is a relationship between region within the Americas and perceptions of corruption.

Null Hypothesis: There is no relationship between region in the Americas and the perceptions of corruption.

\(H_0: C_{NA} = C_{LA}\) where \(C\) is the perception of corruption by region.

Alternative Hypothesis: There is a relationship between region and the perceptions of corruption.

\(H_A: C_{NA} \neq C_{LA}\)

Based on our calculated p value of 0.1368 and \(\alpha = 0.05\), we cannot reject the null hypothesis since \(p >= \alpha\).

Life Ladder in Asia vs Europe

Aforementioned, we believed there would be a cultural difference in Europe and Asia. To further examine this, we did another hypothesis test looking at life ladder between Asia and Europe. We wonder if a different input on what happiness is or what satisfaction in life is may contribute to a relationship between continent and life ladder index.

Null Hypothesis: There is no relationship between the median of life ladder between continents. \(H_0: L_A = L_E\) where \(L\) is life ladder index.

Alternative Hypothesis: There is a relationship between the median life ladder index and continents. \(H_A: L_A \neq L_E\)

Based on the p value of 0, we can reject the null hypothesis since \(\alpha = 0.05\) and \(p < \alpha\). When increasing the number of reps, \(p = 0\), so we can reject the null and believe that there is a relationship between life ladder index and continent.

Single Regression: Freedom to Make Life Choices and Continents

We choose Africa as our baseline to do the regression since it had proportionally the lowest high freedom index and high life ladder. It also had the highest proportion of high perceptions of corruption. We wanted to expand on our hypothesizes by creating a linear regression for freedom to make life choices and continent, as we had seen a relationship between continent and freedom to make life choices in Africa and Europe.

Variable Estimate Standard Error Statistic p-value
(Intercept) 0.6924929 0.0057692 120.032969 0

continentsAsia 0.0538083 0.0078790 6.829293 0
continentsEurope 0.0728654 0.0079742 9.137682 0
continentsOceania 0.2241930 0.0243701 9.199499 0

Based on these results, we found statistically significant relationships between continent and freedom to make life choices, for all continents. The results suggest that, on average, we expect freedom to make life choices to be 0.1 units higher in the Americas, 0.05 units higher in Asia, 0.07 units higher in Europe, and 0.2 units higher in Oceania, all relative to Africa.

Multiple Regression: Confounders with Freedom to Make Life Choices

To dive deeper into our confounders, perceptions of corruption and life ladder, we did a multiple regression with freedom to make life choices, continent, perceptions of corruption, and life ladder.

Next, we created a multiple regression model that included our confounding variables: perceptions of corruption and life ladder score. We saw statistically significant relationships for Europe and Oceania, but not the Americas and Asia. On average, we expect the freedom to make life choices in Europe to be 0.05 units lower than in Africa when keeping perceptions of corruption and life ladder score constant. On average, we expect the freedom to make life choices in Oceania to be 0.04 units lower than in Africa when keeping perceptions of corruption and life ladder score constant.

Discussion

Through this project, we wanted to observe how the freedom to make life choices is perceived across different countries, continents, and regions. Stratifying our analysis by geographical groups allowed us to postulate whether regional cultural norms and historical events relevant to certain geographies may have influenced outcomes. Our boxplot visualizations allowed us to easily compare the median perception of freedom across different continents. Furthermore, the hypothesis tests that we ran allowed us to directly compare multiple continents and regions on selected indices. The tests were: freedom to make life choices in Europe versus Africa, perceptions of corruption in Europe versus Asia, perceptions of corruption by region in the Americas, and life ladder in Europe versus Asia. These were chosen primarily based on visual inferences from our graphs and calculated summary statistics and proportions.

We chose to use Africa as our baseline based on our calculated proportions, which showed that Africa had the lowest proportion of high freedom to make life choices and high life ladder and the highest proportion of high perceptions of corruption. This seemed to generally be the continent with the worst scores. Our simple regression model analysis supports our primary assertion that there is a relationship between continent and freedom to make life choices. However, our multiple regression model indicates that there is a more nuanced relationship between these variables as the inclusion of potential confounders, perception of corruption and life ladder score, changed the relationship seen. This model showed that when holding the perception of corruption and life ladder score constant, the freedom to make life choices index decreased, on average, in Europe and Oceania compared to Africa.

Asia had the most variation in index scores from 2007 to 2022, reflecting its vast size and diversity. This can be attributed to the fact that the Asia continent group contains several trans-continental regions, such as the Europe & Central Asia region. When looking at summary statistics for the scores stratified by region as opposed to continent, we see the mean scores change. For example, North America mean scores are skewed higher as they only account for the U.S. and Canada, and this region has the highest minimum score and the lowest standard deviation. We also noted that East Asia & Pacific mean scores skew higher as they group Australia and New Zealand with countries in East Asia.

When looking at the relationship between the perception of corruption and freedom to make life choices by continent, we noticed negative linear trends; as perception of corruption increased, freedom to make life choices generally decreased. In the Americas, Asia, and Europe, there are many data points indicating high perceptions of corruption correlated with high freedom to make life choices. Adding a third variable, time, to these graphs may broaden understanding of historical trends. However, we were primarily interested in investigating the relationship between the two variables, so we chose not to filter by year. Future research could expand on this analysis by incorporating time. The summary statistics stratified by continent show interesting trends. Europe has the largest standard deviation. A limitation of our research is that we cannot separate Eastern and Western European countries in our analysis. Given the historically different political structures of these nations, combining them into a single group may cloud underlying trends and may explain the wide range of perceptions of corruption scores calculated for the continent. Both Africa and Asia have incredibly low minimum scores, which we found surprising based on the freedom index scores for these continents. Further research could explore which specific countries might be outliers accounting for those data.

When looking at the relationship between life ladder index and freedom to make life choices, we see positive linear trends; as perception of life ladder status increased, freedom to make life choices generally increased. Notably, no one country ranked their life ladder score above an 8 on a scale of 1-10. The only country that ranked themselves below a 2 was located in Asia (minimum: 1.28). The life ladder status for the Americas was lower than we initially expected. This may support the idea that North American culture lacks global awareness and its citizens do not recognize how privileged they are globally. Some of it is most likely Latin American citizens who have struggled through colonization and imperialism. However, Latin America and the Caribbean combined with North America does not create a full picture for either group of countries. Africa has the lowest mean (4.37) and lowest maximum (6.24) life ladder score, which could comment on the somewhat recent colonization and exploitation of many African countries.

With our proportions and hypotheses, we see a general trend arise between continents. Oceania has the highest proportion of high freedom index, high life ladder, and low corruption. Overall, Oceania seems to be doing well, although the sample size is small since it only includes two countries: New Zealand and Australia. All continents seem to have a majority high freedom index (over 0.5 proportionally). Similarly, all continents except Oceania have a majority of perceptions of high corruption (over 0.5 proportionally). Interestingly, this seems like freedom does not correlate with corruption, and many countries believe their governments are corrupt. Looking at the life ladder proportions, we can see more about the way individuals rate themselves globally. Overall, Africa has the highest percentage (0.832 proportionally) with the lowest life ladder rating and 0% in the highest life ladder rating. This fits with many peopleâs perceptions of life on the African continent, although much of this could be explained by recent colonization, famine, and disease. Asia has the second highest proportion for the lowest life ladder rating (0.387 proportionally). Europe has a slightly higher proportion of countries with the highest life ladder rating (0.248) compared to Americas (0.137). Initially, we believed Europeans may be harsher in their rating compared to Americans, who are known for their generally happy dispositions. However, we wonder if the Scandinavian countries as well as other European countriesâ access to healthcare and other social programs improves their ratings. Itâs also important to note unlike most of Europe, the United States is not homogeneous and has clear racial tensions. While Europe has colonized other countries, they tend to believe racism is less of a domestic issue. For many Americans, racism remains at the forefront of the public, as they rate their life ladder lower. However, white Europeans tend to be less concerned with these issues. Itâs also important to note that countries like Australia, New Zealand, North America, and western European countries had lower freedom indexes and higher perceptions of corruption after 2020, or the advent of COVID-19. We believe that, especially in countries with major lock downs like Australia, New Zealand, and some European countries, this changed the freedoms and perceptions of corruption. The United States also decreased after 2020, potentially due to COVID-19 and also potentially due to the 2020 election and its effects. With the increase in alt-right politics across America and Europe, we wonder how the future results will change.

Overall, while our analysis yielded interesting results, there were a few things that we could have approached differently. To begin, the data set we used did not have data for every country in every continent for every year, which poses a limitation to the scope of our study. For example, some countries only had data from 2008-2015, which rendered us unable to observe their long-term changes. Other countries were not in the data set at all. In Oceania, there were only two countries, Australia and New Zealand. This small sample size inclusive of only Western-aligned nations does not provide any information about other islands in Oceania. This raised Oceaniaâs rating higher when not all countries within Oceania are thriving. In addition, when grouping with the country code package, we did not get much information on what countries belong to each continent. For countries like Russia, it could be classified as Europe or Asia. The World Happiness Index does not explain exactly how they collect the data, so details such as whether the participants were surveyed in their native language, how interviewees and surveyors were selected, and whether participants were given clarifying support in answering questions. A random sample conducted in the native language by surveyors highly trained to expertly collect data would be most accurate, as opposed to a convenience sample. Furthermore, more thorough surveys that assessed for other confounders, such as inequality and unemployment, would overcome the limitation of this survey which only includes six factors to explain life evaluations.

Considering our hypotheses, we rejected the null in favor of the alternative for a few. We found an independent relationship between continent and perceptions of corruption in Asia and Europe. We wanted to examine if differences in cultural values by geographical region might explain different views of corruption. Then, we looked at the life ladder difference between Europe and Asia, and rejected the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between continent and life ladder rating. We wondered if cultural differences might explain some of these differences. While corruption may seem more universal, life ladder is more subjective and seems to change by continent. We could not reject the null hypothesis that Latin America and North America have no differences in perceptions of corruption. This was surprising, as we believed that Latin America and the Caribbean might rate their corruption higher, due to past colonization, instability in the region, and US-sponsored coup dâetats. However, it seems like North American countries believe they have similar levels of corruption. We also examined whether Europe and Africa had a difference in freedom to make life choices. We could reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between continent and freedom to make life choices. Aforementioned, the colonization of Africa could drastically affect this rating. For these hypotheses, we did not sort by time at all, as time was not a variable we were examining. However, if we were to dive more into specific examples we could look at change over time or check dependence relationships with time and the perceptions of corruption or life ladder indices.

If we could redo our analysis, we would ideally collect our own data by randomly sampling individuals from each country. While this would be time-consuming and outside the scope of our project, it would allow us to collect more reliable and relevant data. In addition, if we had chosen a research question centered on a more specific geographical region, we could have dived deeper into specific countries or continents and perhaps may have found more concrete results. If we instead examined outcomes after a specific historical event that occurred during the study period, we could potentially see very interesting results about how political and social turmoil may affect different countries. We were not able to stratify by time, which could have been another test. Exploring this additional variable in the context of the variables we examined may have strengthened the scope of our analysis and fostered deeper insights into our discussion.

Overall, this study shed light on some of the geographical variations in societal perceptions of social rankings. It suggests the importance of expanded accurate data collection to understand the impacts of major political and social events on public freedom to make life choices.
